column168: On August 1, 2020, R+L Carriers(RLC) personnel at the Sacramento terminal observed a cargo leak from trailer SF1953 located at the above-referenced address. Approximately one-half gallon of paint was released to the trailer and pavement underneath the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Ancon Services(AS) to initiate corrective actions. Crews identified a single damaged 1-gallon paint container and removed from the load for disposal. AS deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and pavement surfaces. All waste paint, spent absorbents, and impacted packing materials were collected and containerized into two(2) 55-gallon drums and staged at OSD for profiling. Once the cleanup was complete, AS secured the scene and demobilized.

08/05/20, at 09:42 hours, personnel in the Selkirk Yard Selkirk NY Mile post QG 15 reported that they observed the GATX51682 leaking from the protective housing area. The GATX51682 a residue DOT 111A100W1 UN 1307 Xylenes Class 3 PGIII. The Railcar was isolated and BNSF Corporation, NYS DEC and NYS transportation were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2020080500104). CSX Hazmat Manager D. Scoons, Responded to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon climbing the railcar and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the leak was coming from the bottom of the liquid line valve. Valve appeared to not be properly seated on the flange. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael Doring 225-892-6961.Ball valve assembly was removed and properly reinstalled on railcar. Railcar was cleaned and purged and will be home shopped under a OTMA for requalification. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1   Cause Code: 292 NARRI:

column168: On August 14, 2020 at 0830 ET, XPO Logistics terminal XDY contacted ERTS regarding the release of UN1170 190 Proof Ethanol. It was reported that a 5 gallon poly jug in a cardboard box was torn during loading operations and released approximately 1 ounce of material inside the trailer. The material released ethanol had evaporated before the spill was found by terminal personnel. Prior to contacting ERTS, terminal personnel placed the damaged container into a 20 gallon steel drum. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

The drum arrived at the Veolia Dayton 10-cay in transit facility on August 12, 2020 from Veolia's TSDF in West Carrollton, Ohio en route to Port Arthur, TX. When the trailer was being unloaded, the material handler observed some liquid in the nose of the trailer on the floor. The leaking drum was identified and removed from the trailer to be over packed. Upon inspection, the drum was discovered to be leaking from the chime on the bottom of the drum. Further inspection of the drum showed a significant amount of rust on the bottom of the container. Veolia believes the rust is an indication of degradation of the container. Due to the viscosity of the material we did not see specifically how large the hole or failure was. Approximately 5 gallons of material leaked from the container. Floor dry and spill pads were used to soak up the material. All spill debris and contaminated PPE were placed in the a new drum for final disposal.
column169: Because this appears to be a degradation issue of the drum, Veolia has communicated to the original generator and the original transporter requesting that they inspect the integrity of drums prior to shipment.

On 08/11/20, at 0917, S FRA inspector in Selkirk Yard discovered TILX362495, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from the manway cover. The car was isolated and CHEMTREC, NYS DEC and NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2020-0811-00094. Miller Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a damaged nozzle gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Andrew Schwartz 203-905-7102 anschwa@equinor.com. Contractor personnel replaced the manway nozzle gasket, secured the manway cover and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. A 7.1 is not required  Cause Code: 209 NARRI: 5
column169: (NAR: 209 What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover Why Failed: Gasket deteriorated )

column168: The driver arrived at Clarios, LLC to be loaded he was told to open the trailer doors and back up to the dock. Hee was not allowed out of his vehicle nor was he allowed on their dock while they loaded him. Once the driver was loaded they allowd him to pull forward and seal the trailer. As per company policy the driver took pictures of the load / Securments and placards issued to the load which were UN2291 Poison placards. The driver closed the trailer doors and sealed the load. The driver travelled 150 miles to the AC&T truck stop in Hagerstown, MD where he spent the night. The next morning he found  liquid standing on the left rear of the trailer and observed liquid in small drips had dropped to the graound. The driver under RDX Safety direction took appropriate action. Lewis Enviromentat was call out. When they arrivewd They learned the driver had both SDS sheets for the 2291 Poison and a 3077 Corrosive.  The liquid was PH Tested and was found to be a Ph of 0 making it a HIGHLY Corrosive product.  The barrels were standard steel drims  not lined to handle this type of a corrosive. The barrel that was leaking was loaded mid way up the left side of the trailer and the acid had eaten the bottone seam of the leaking barrel. The leaking barrel and the adjacent pallet had both damaged barrels and the leaking product removed the paint allong the leaking seam. This was not viewable by the driver after the loading was completed. However the driver was restricted from viewing the loading and this was intentionally hidden in the center of the load Per the lewis Enviromental scene supervisor.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Driver advised when he started unloading product was spraying from a pinhole in his hose.  1-2 cups sprayed out by the time he got it shut down and the air pressure stopped forcing product out of the hole.  In was in a containment area where they rinse hoses out after delivery.  He only had 10psi on at the time.  The hose is designed above 100psi.  There was evidence of tankwash damage to the hose usually from sending the wand up inside the hose.  However we also found that the hose was past our internal inspection timeframe of one year.
column169: The driver was brought in for training for letting his hose inspections lapse.  There is a tag on the end of the hose that they are supposed to be looking at when hooking up for offloading.  We also reminded the entire tankwash network we utilize about not putting pressure washer ends inside of the hoses.

column168: Switch crew in Paducah Yard noticed a strong odor coming from subject tank car.  Crew notified on duty trainmaster and dispatcher.  General Car foreman and on duty carman performed inspection and found a loose manway bolt and pinched manway gasket.  Customer, Celanese, was notified and agreed if car were not going to be moved there would be no hazard overnight and agreed to come inspect in the morning.  (This occurred at approximately 2016 hours 8/18/2020).  The morning of 8/19/2020 a representative from Celanese confirmed a pinched manway gasket and contracted Rail Services, Inc to come change out the gasket.  NRC and Chemtrec were notified the evening of 8/18/2020  This car was found to have been shipped to UTLX facility in Ohio as a residue for maintenance.  Upon being opened by UTLX it was found to be loaded and was enroute back to Calvert City when the leak was discovered.  It is believed the damage to gasket occurred when it was opened in Ohio.

column168: Loaded tank car described as UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid, Class 8 / PG II, RQ (Hydrochloric Acid) was discovered in rail transportation with product adhering to side of tank car. Inspectors were unable to identify the leak source of the commodity.  Duration of the release is undeterminded due to the shippment being in transit storage for several days.  Consignee's hazmat response (Specilized Professional Services) team identified the leak and repaired rupture disc gasket and neutralized the residual product on the valves, fittings and car body.

While performing an in transit load check, a driver identified a release coming from his transport van trailer. The driver implemented contingency plan controls to minimize the impact of the release to the environment. An internal response team was dispatched to assist. In appropriate personal protective equipment, the response team was successful in identifying the compromised container, salvage packing it into an authorized container and remediation of the impacted areas. The impact of this release was confined to the transport trailer and asphalt, with no threat to life, storm drains, water ways, or soil. The container and transport trailer was shipped to its final destination without further incident.

The release in the trailer has already been cleaned up and the trailer has moved on, however, the release impacted at least 5 drain basins and a nearby brook. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to clean the impacted roadway and the impacted rains and creek. The contractor utilized granular absorbents to clean the impacted roadway and utilized a vacuum truck to collect the impacted water from the storm drains. The FD flushed the drains as per NJ DEP instructions and added liquid waste was collected. Pads and boom were placed in the creek and the environmental contractor will perform several more site inspections and change outs b order of the NJ DEP. All waste will be containerized and taken for disposal

column168: On August 3, 2020 at 09:40, the Trainmaster at Conrail's Port Reading Yard notified that NJ DOT Inspector  Alan Fisher had found UTLX 202632, a residue tank car containing Methyl Methacrylate UN 1247 leaking.  The source of the release was a faulty vacuum relief valve (VRV). The tank car was isolated and Marion  Environmental Inc. a Conrail approved response contractor was dispatched to the scene as well as Joe  Caccamo Conrail Hazardous Material Manager. Upon additional inspection it was confirmed that product  vapors were escaping from the VRV. The tank car was depressurized and the VRV was removed. A 2.5"  steel plug was then properly secured in its place. The tank car was placed on hold until the Shipper and  car owner secured One Time Movement Approval to send the tank car to Home Shop for repairs.   Cause code: 1125 NARRI: 5(4+3+0) X (2+0)= 70

column168: UTLX 210973 was found releasing diesel fuel in the Union Pacific Nampa Yard. The release was due to six swing bolts on the manway not being secured. H20 Environmental responded, secured the manway and wiped down the car.

Tank car was reported by yard personnel to be leaking liquid product from the top of the car and a strong odor of alcohol. Inspection found the manway swingbolts to be improperly applied, 3 of 6 bolts were over-tightened causing the manway lid to be warped applying uneven pressure to gasket causing release. Inlet gasket was impressed on one side so a new nozzle gasket was installed and lid was secured. Car release back to transportation and continue on to destination.
column169: Proper inspection before loading, unloading, and before releasing for shipment. Apply even torque to all swingbolts during preparation for transportation.

column168: On 8/11/2020 This shipment was discovered to contain hidden dangerous goods during the physical inspection process at the DHL LGA Service Center, located at 230-19 Rockaway Blvd, Springfield Gardens, NY 11413. Transportation by road has been confirmed.

On August 18, 2020, at approximately 2:10 pm CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (RLC) was parked at the above-referenced location when the unit's driver observed a shifted pallet in the trailer. As a result of the load shift, approximately one(1) cup of UN1814 potassium hydroxide was released from one(1) 5-gallon pail to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from NRC Environmental Services(NRC) to initiate corrective actions. Crews collected the damaged pale and re-stacked the remaining cargo for safe transportation. While unloading the pallet, crews discovered a damaged 5-gallon pale of a non-regulated glucose that also released to the trailer floor. NRC personnel then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. All potassium hydroxide was collected and a containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum and the glucose impacted material was collected in one(1) 15-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal. NRC personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

On August 18, 2020, at approximately 12:15 pm CDT, a representative with R+L Carriers(RLC) at the above-referenced location observed a damaged bag of Calcium Peroxide(UN1457) at dock door 9. As a result of the damage, approximately 4 cups of UN1457 was released to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from NRC Environmental Services(NRC) to initiate corrective actions. Crews removed the box and utilized a vacuum to collect the released product from the trailer floor. All calcium peroxide impacted material was collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal. NRC personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized. ,

column168: FRA HM Inspector R. Boyington identified the GBRX 700756 as possibly leaking with wetness observed near the manway while the car was in the train.  Local operations isolated the car and setout to track 601 where it was inspected by US Ecology.  At approximately 14:00 PST US Ecology was able to determine that there had been a small (<1 gallon) release of Gas Oil to the car body.  The cause was due to a torn manway nozzle gasket and two less than tool tight manway swing bolts.  A new manway gasket was installed and the car was secured, cleaned and released for transportation. On 8/26/20, at 1955 hrs. an FRA Inspector in the CSXT Rockdale Yard discovered TILX161786, a residue tank car of Phosphoric Acid Solution, leaking from the secondary closure of the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and EcoLab/Nutrien, the NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2020-0826-00370. RMS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the valve open and product migrating through the secondary closure threads. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Sergio Navarro, 970-222-3655. Contractor personnel closed the valve handle and taped the threads on the secondary closure nut and decontaminated the valve fitting cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 150 NARRI: 5

column168: Upon arrival at the destination terminal the tote was discovered leaking inside the trailer. Investigation of the incident had revealed that another skid was double stacked next to the tote. The skid fell over on top of the tote causing the tote to crack and material to be released. The released material was absorbed using absorbent pads and containerized to be disposed of properly. The damaged tote was secured to prevent further release until contents could be transferred into another tote.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the other freight been properly blocked and braced for transit. The responsible employee involved in loading the freight was disciplined and re-trained per company policy to prevent future incidents from occurring. This incident was used in a monthly training topic to illustrate the importance of proper blocking and bracing procedures.

column168: Heritage Transport driver stopped for lunch at the Travel Center in Refugio, Texas. Upon returning from lunch, he noticed a small droplet on the ground under his trailer. He opened the door of the trailer to investigate further and discovered that a drum was leaking very lightly. He immediately set up some spill pads and booms around the drum to stop and contain the leak. He put some spill absorbent material over the small drip under the trailer and then called his dispatcher to report the spill. The dispatcher instructed him to call the Heritage 1-800-SPILL number to dispatch an in-house crew to come and over pack the leaking drum and clean-up the spilled material from inside of the trailer and the small amount on the pavement.
column169: Retraining on recognizing insufficient and potentially compromised containers will be recommended for staff at generator's site. column168: On August 24,2020, a box truck operated by R+L Carriers(RLC) was parked at the above-referenced location when the driver observed a cargo leak. Upon further inspection, one battery had tipped over during transit and released approximately two(2) gallons of battery acid to the trailer interior and concrete beneath the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LC(FCE) to perform corrective actions. FCE deployed acid neutralizer and granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and concrete then collected them with hand tools. All impacted absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. The battery was strapped against the inner wall of the truck to secure for transport. Once the cleanup was complete, FCE collected the waste and demobilized.

column168: During sort operations at tne ANCK ramp in Anchorage, AK a fiberboard box associated with tracking number 771196693895 was selected for inspection by US Customs agents. The shipment originated in Guangzhou, China and was transiting to an apartment in Philadelphia, PA. It contained parts labeled as Airbag Gas Generators, which apparently should have been prepared as UN3268 Safety Devices. Some of parts had labeling indicating manufacture by Autoliv Inc. Autoliv was contacted, and management staff there indicated the parts appeared to counterfeit. The FedEx PowerShip label and a pro forma invoice included with the package listed the contents as sample plastic covers and sample iron linings. There were no dangerous goods markings or labels on the package, no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment, and the packaging was not UN Specification rated. , Upon discovery, the package was held for US Customs pending further disposition instruction.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop in order to perform his second  Load Check.  During the check of vehicle and load, driver noted a moist spot on the pallet.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to  decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.

column168: Drum was picked up at customer location and brought back to branch for transport to final destination. The next day drum was discovered to be bulging. A field services crew was dispatched. Crew safely relieved the pressure, and packaged the drum into a proper salvage drum. The drum was moved and prepped for transport. The drum, unknown by the branch employees started to react again. Due to it being placed into a salvage drum no one noticed the reaction until enough pressure had built up to blow the lid off both the original container and the salvage drum. Paint was contained in the salvage drum, with minor spraying on the out side of the salvage drum. A crew was brought in, put on all the proper PPE, and evaluated the contents of the drum. The reaction was stopped by solidifying the paint. The waste was placed into proper containers and shipped off to the final disposal sight. The damaged drum, and salvage drum, along with all PPE, and spill clean up material we also disposed of properly.
column169: The customer has looked at their process for disposing of waste and have put procedures in place to prevent this issue from happening again. Our employees have been retrained on container evaluation.

column168: A household hazardous waste collection event was held by the Town of Taunton on Saturday, August, 29, 2020.  Veolia was the subcontractor hired to manage the event and transport the collected materials for ultimate disposal. The day of the event, the weather was heavy rain due to remnants of a tropical storm passing through the area. At the end of the event, all containers of household hazardous waste were loaded onto the Veolia vehicle. Many of the containers were wet due to the heavy rain. Following the event, the vehicle was driven to Veolia's 10 transit facility in Marlborough, MA and parked there over the remainder of the weekend. On Monday morning, Veolia employees returning to the office noticed a pool of liquid under the vehicle. It is estimated that approximately 5 gallons of paint related material leaked out of a pinhole on a reconditioned drum. The hole appears to be a defect in the reconditioned container. Employees reinspected all containers for leaks and overpacked the leaking container for continued transportation.
column169: Veolia managers have re-evaluated the use of reconditioned drums. In addition, the incident was reviewed with the employees who worked at the HHW collection event. Veolia typically performs a thorough inspection of containers for leaks prior to shipping however, due to the wet weather and the drums being wet from the rain, the leak was hard to identify. Veolia will continue to do proper inspections and will look at other ways to perform inspections during poor weather conditions.

column161: LISA MARTIN ON BEHALF OF HERITAGE TRANSPORT
column168: Description of Events & Package Failure: On August 20, 2020, at approximately 12:37 pm an Heritage employee operating a fork-truck was moving a pallet of waste printing ink in 55-gallon containers to be loaded onto a trailer.  While driving, one container fell from the pallet onto the asphalt parking lot at the Part B Permitted Treatment, Storage and Disposal Facility located at Heritage Environmental Services, 8525 NE 38th Street, Kansas City, Missouri. The asphalt parking area where the spill occurred was within the spill containment/control structure at this facility.  The container landed on its side and the lid came off resulting in approximately fifty gallons or four-hundred-eighty-six pounds of waste printing ink being spilled.  The fork-truck operator and facility employees immediately began spill response and control procedures.  Response time for the containment and cleanup was approximately 1.5 hours.  Heritage personnel acted appropriately and promptly in accordance with the Contingency Plan to contain the material.  Material Involved in Incident: Approximately fifty gallons of waste printing ink was released, identified on line 1 of manifest 021493822JJK, RQ,UN1210,WASTE PRINTING INK,3,PGIII,(D001 @ 100LBS),ERG#129.  Heritage Transport had possession of this material as it was manifested to Rineco Chemical Industries, LLC in Benton, Arkansas.  Approximately 1,024 pounds of clay absorbent and rags were recovered and placed into two 85-gallon containers for proper disposal.
column169: Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence:  Based on the incident review, the pallet that the shipper provided for the containers was not adequately constructed to hold the weight of the containers.  When the pallet of containers was moved, the pallet broke because the boards were not strong enough to hold the weight of the containers.  When the pallet broke, this caused the drum to fall, then the lid to bend and the contents of the container to spill out.  Heritage conducted an incident review and training on August 31, 2020.  Heritage employees will replace insufficient, broken or damaged pallets when needed.

On August 30th, 2020 at 1307 personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard discovered DOWX73060, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acrylate Stabilized leaking from Pressure Relief Device. The car was isolated and ROHMM & HAAS, New Orleans Fire Dept., Louisiana State Police, were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2020-08-30-00031. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that a small vapor release from the pressure relief device. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Brian Hopkins 989-636-1483. Contractor personnel inspected the tank car a found that the man-way lid gasket was damaged, but not the source of the vapor release. The source of the release was from the pressure relief device, although it was found to be free of defects and operating properly. We conclude that the release from the pressure relief device was from handling of the car during transportation. SPSI replaced the man-way gasket and inspected the pressure relief device. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. NARRI Cause Code 700 Hydraulic Surge NARRI 2(5+3+5) X (2+0) = 52. Further review of yard video showed no signs of over handling while in the CSX New Orleans terminal. Car was delivered from the UPRR.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A Semi-truck and cargo tank trailer own by Seymour Transport and operated by Grammer Logistics, DOT #184668, was hauling a load of Liquified Petroleum Gas (Propane/Propylene) on I-10 east south of Baton Rouge, LA near Prairieville, LA and had a pressure release device (PRD) open and start relieving pressure into the atmosphere. The driver of the semi-tractor and trailer stopped on the shoulder of Interstate I-10 to investigate the problem when he saw the PRD releasing pressure into the air. The pressure on the cargo tank trailer was 150 psi and the set pressure of the PRD was 265 psi, so he immediately called 911. LA Hazmat, Prairieville FD, ST. George Parish FD and LA Department of Environmental Air Quality arrived on scene.  The LA hazmat department arrived and started spraying water onto the cargo trailer and the Department of Environmental Air Quality started monitoring air quality in the area. Another cargo trailer was dispatched to the scene to transfer product from the leaking transport. The propane was transferred into another cargo tank. The duration of the incident was approximately 6 hours.  It was determined upon inspection of the cargo tank and the PRD that a baffle that was welded to the interior wall of the cargo tank had broken loose from its welds and hit the PRD shearing it off inside the trailer causing the stem to get knocked of its seat allowing vapors to escape into the atmosphere.
column169: All inspections will be done in accordance with DOT-SP 14689 dated April 22, 2016  7.   SAFETY CONTROL MEASURES:  a.  PACKAGING - Prescribed packagings are DOT Specification MC-331 cargo tank motor vehicles with a  water capacity greater than 3,500 gallons, manufactured to the DOT MC-331 specification,  constructed of QT steel by Trinity Industries, Inc. between 1996 and 2006 with baffle support clips  welded directly to the inside of the cargo tank wall without the use of pads.  b.  INSPECTIONS AND TESTS – As part of the pressure test required by § 180.407(g), the required  internal inspection must include a detailed inspection of appurtenances (baffles, bolting, clips,  pads, piping or other internals), their attachment to the cargo tank wall and the interior wall of  the cargo tank.  (1)  Baffles that cannot be inspected as installed shall be detached or removed for inspection and  evaluation.  (2)  The area of direct weld attachment to the shell of baffles, or clips must be inspected for  cracking, corrosion, weld defects or other defects that may cause the baffle or clip to detach from  the shell.  Non- ferrous baffles or clips must be examined by the Liquid Penetrant method; ferrous  baffles or clips must be examined by the Wet Fluorescent Magnetic Particle method.  Non-Destructive  Examination (test methodology, tester qualifications, and documentation) must be in accordance with ASME Section V.  (i)  Any cracked or corroded clips must be replaced with material whose properties are equivalent  to that of the cargo tank wall, or a material approved by a Design Certified Engineer (DCE).  (ii)  Any damaged, cracked or corroded baffles attached directly to the shell must be repaired, r replaced.

column168: On August 7,2020, at approximately 3:06 pm CDT, facility personnel at the above-referenced R +L Carriers(RLC) location punctured one(1) 55-gallon drum, containing sulfuric acid, with a forklift. As a result of the puncture, approximately three(3) gallons on UN1830 was released to the loading dock floor and pallet. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Ancon Services(AS) to initiate corrective actions. AS personnel transferred the UN1830 material from the damaged 15-gallon drum into three(3) 5-gallon pail. Crews deployed a neutralizing agent to lower the pH of the material. Crews utilized a pH test strip to ensure the material was neutralized. AS personnel then deployed granular absorbent to the loading dock floor and worked them in using hand tools. Crews then broke down the pallet to take for disposal. All UN1830 impacted material was collected and containerized in three(3) 5-gallon pails and 2 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. AS personnel noted no further actions required and crews demobilized.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. Upon opening trailer to offload at customer location, a leak was discovered. Site was secured, and Clean Harbors Environmental was dispatched to assess and perform cleanup. Upon inspection, free product was detected on trailer floor and contained within trailer. There was no impact to ground surface or threat to impact state waters. Clean Harbors Environmental proceeded to offload the trailer and discovered eight 5-gallon pails of UN1760, which were damaged inside the trailer. Approximately 38 gallons of free product had released from the pails. Clean Harbors Environmental cleaned the trailer floor, wiped adjacent freight, and overpacked the damaged pails into one 55-gallon recovery drum. Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures.

column168: On August 26,2020, at approximately 1:00 p.m. CDT, at the above referenced R+L Carriers(RL) terminal, six(6) batteries were discovered damaged from a mid-transit load shift. As a result, approximately ten CIO) gallons of battery acid released to the trailer interior and concrete loading dock surface. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LC(ER) to perform corrective actions. ER personnel utilized sodium bicarbonate to neutralize the trailer and concrete surfaces. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the battery acid-impacted trailer surface and swept them in with hand tools. ER personnel then repeated this process under the trailer on the concrete surface. Crews utilized absorbent pads to collect the battery acid from the other impacted skids. All battery acid impacted material was collected and containerized into four(4) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. The six(6) damaged batteries were placed into six(6) 55-gallon drums for transport and recycling. ER personnel then repalletized a different skid of six(6) batteries that shifted during transit. ER personnel noted no further actions required onsite and demobilized.

column168: After the loading process was complete, the loading hose was cleared of liquids.  Upon disconnecting the loading hose, the driver discovered the internal and external were not retaining the product.   The driver connected the hose back on to the loading/unloading valve to contain the release.   The release occurred into the 2.5 gallon spill bucket  and onto concrete surface in the containment  area.   On-site personnel told the driver to go inside and as a precaution evacuated the containment area.  Our driver tried to refuse but AMPAC staff insisted - the driver finally complied.  On-site response staff took control of the tanker trailer and attempted to empty the tanker by  pumping the material back into their tanks.  This was unsuccessful.  A second Clean Harbors  Environmental truck was dispatched to empty the tanker, utilizing a vacuum trailer.  No further  incident or spill happened.  The empty tank trailer was then rendered out of service and taken  to the tank shop for inspection.
column169: This particular tank was thoroughly inspected to include gaskets, valves and sealing devices. This  tank came from the factory with stainless steel valves and Teflon gaskets.  They should not  have deteriorated as they are impervious to solvents.  We have since learned from the tank inspector  that a small amount of sand had collected in the valve channel prohibiting it from closing securely.   We believe the small amount of sand may have come from a prior load of non-hazardous water,  which may have had small sand particles in it.  We are contemplating not using this certified tank for  non-hazardous water moving forward so as to prevent recurrence.

column168: On August 5,2020, at approximately 3:00 p.m. CDT, facility personnel at the above-referenced R +L Carriers(RLC) location discovered one(1) 330-gallon tote, containing yellow printing ink, that was damaged during a mid-transit load shift. As a result of the damage, approximately one(1) gallon of product released from the tote to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LC(ER) to perform corrective actions. ER inserted absorbent pads into the damaged tote's discharge fitting to secure the release, then deployed additional absorbent pads to the ink-impacted trailer interior. Crew members then utilized one(1) forklift to raise the damaged tote in order to gravity-transfer all remaining product into one(1) new 330-gallon tote. Gravity transfer operations failed due to the viscosity of the product, prompting ER to halt remedial action and secure the damaged tote with poly sheeting. RLC personnel advised CES to leave the secured tote onsite and demobilize. ER secured the site and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: On August 26,2020, at approximately 3:30 p.m. CDT, at the above referenced R+L Carriers 1 (RLC) terminal, one(1) 5-gallon metal pail of paint was damaged by other freight during transit.  As a result, approximately five(5) gallons of paint released to the trailer surface. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from ACV Enviro(AC\4 to perform corrective actions. ACV personnel unloaded the other freight and utilized absorbent pads to collect the free product. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer surface and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and the damaged pail were collected and containerized into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ACV personnel noted no further actions required onsite and demobilized.

column168: A FedEx Pak containing was observed to contain undeclared DG at the origin station AFWND, in Fort Worth, TX. The pak contained a 946 ml can of AC Delco Top Engine Cleaner. Per the SDS document associated with the product, this commodity is classified as Division 2.1 dangerous goods, specifically UN1950, Aerosols, flammable. There were no Dangerous Goods markings or labels on the FedEx Pak, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

Facility personnel immediately put down absorbent to contain the release. Facility personnel immediately put down absorbent to contain the release. column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: On 8/14/2020 at 1240 hours, a Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) conductor reported tank car UTLX 125697 Ieaking while in the KCS Beaumont, TX rail yard. UTLX 125697 contained a load of waste sulphuric acid. KCS Environmental and Hazmat mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate and mitigate the release. Upon arrival, the response contractor found the release emanating from the non-reclosing pressure relief device- the frangable rupture disc on UTLX 125697 had opened. While replacing the frangable rupture disc, the responder noticed that it had been installed up-side-down. Because the wrong side of the disc had been exposed to product, the disc had corroded, thus causing the failure. A new frangable rupture disc was correctly installed, product removed from the outside of the car, and all other closures checked for securement. Once the car had been secured, it was released back into transportation. Estimated product release was approximately one gallon. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal InJury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. (NAR: 439)

column168: During sort operations at the GEGR ramp in Spokane, WA a strong odor was observed coming from the aft bulk compartment, designated ABK, of inbound Flight 0907 arriving at GEGR from the MEMH hub in Memphis. Upon further inspection the source of the odor was determined to be a United States Postal Service package leaking a paint like substance. Due to possible damage to the aircraft the box was opened to identify the substance to properly clean the plane. The package contained a gallon can of Evercoat Finish Sand 4:1 Hybrid Polyester Primer Surfacer. There were no dangerous goods markings or labels on the package and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The postal tracking number was 9405536895232996247826 and the USPS D and R tag number was ASLYEZFYCM. All contents of the ABK were USPS packages. Following spill cleanup FedEx Aircraft Maintenance staff inspected the plane. The USPS Postal Inspector was contacted to take possession of the involved shipment.

column168: A fiberboard  box, tracking number 720690731769, containing inner plastic 3.78 L bottles of Maxim Neutral Disinfectant was observed leaking during PM sort operations at the ALTR origin ramp in Atlanta, GA. column168: On 8/30/2020 at 5:24 PM, a Kansas City Southern Railway ( KCS) employee the KCS Environmental & Hazmat Department that loaded tank car UTLX 668204 was found leaking from the top of the car while in the KCS rail yard in Port Arthur , TX. A railroad qualified response contractor was mobilized to investigate and mitigate the leak. Once on site, responders found six manway securement bolts less than tool tight. The gasket was present and  in good condition . Responders secured the manway , cleaned the residual product from the outside of the car, and verified all other closures were tool tight. The car was then released back into transportation.  File note: Item 19 the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a "bulk" shipment , aka one car load , therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantity this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway ( KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases ( NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. NAR's are troublesome to all because they are , large , preventable. For non accident release and to then facilities corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. column168: On August 14, 2020, at approximately 2:15 p.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers (RLC) was operating at the above-referenced location when one(1) pallet containing twenty-four (24) batteries tipped over during transit. As a result, approximately approximately four(4) gallons of battery acid released from three(3) batteries to the cardboard box exterior, trailer interior, and concrete surface. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Cowlitz Clean Sweep, Inc(CCS) to perform the necessary corrective action. Crews noted three(3) of the 24 batteries in the trailer were shifted by a 20 degree angle, but not damaged. CCS personnel neutralized the trailer surface with sodium bicarbonate then deployed granular absorbents to the impacted surface and swept them in with hand tools. Simple green was then deployed to collect any residual product. Crews deployed additional granular absorbents to the trailer surface and swept them in with hand tools. CCS personnel repeated this process on the asphalt surface below the trailer. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one(1) cubic yard box for transport and disposal. CCS personnel noted no further actions required onsite and demobilized.

column168: Driver of the fuel truck was attempting to enter Hwy20 traveling on Roswell Rd at approximately(0740), on 08/08/20. As he was attempting to make the maneuver he felt the rear wheel lift off the road. He attempted to correct the position but over corrected resulting in a rollover. When the vehicle came to a rest the driver exited the cab. He called 911. The Marietta FD were on the scene in approximately 5-10 minutes. Upon arrival the MFD crews along with Marietta Public Works had placed a sand berm across Roswell Road approximately 4 feet wide by 18" tall spanning all four lanes downgradient from the truck. Remtech Engineers arrived on site(0940), Marietta Wrecker Service was on site assisting MFD with recovery of the fuel that was Ieaking from the tanker into a containment pool with a small air powered pump(placing fuel into drums). After conferring with fire command and MWS, equipment was moved into position to stabilize the truck for hot tapping the tank and pulling product from the three compartments. Remtech utilized one of our two vacuum trucks on scene to remove fuel while the second truck was set up as emergency containment/ recovery downstream in case of a breach. The fuel spill was contained approximately 20 minutes after the incident occurred. See enclosed photos.
